’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Huppert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Hugbert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hubert Jernegan was born in 1165, in Horham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Horham Jernegan. He had at least 1 son with Maude de Watheby. He died in 1205, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1165–1205":"1165–1205","–Female":"Surnud","1195–1239":"1195–1239","1135–1182":"1135–1182","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1135":"1135","1165":"1165","1195":"1195","1182":"1182","Horham, Hartismere, Suffolk":"Horham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Horham,  Suffolk":"Horham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1165–1205":"1165–1205","–Female":"Kuollut","1195–1239":"1